subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
This species is unusually distinctive. Males are immediately identifiable by any of the following: forebasitarsus spindly and with black and white tufts, mid leg tarsal segments all elongated, tibial spurs apically pointed and inner hind spur medially bent, and hindbasitarsus irregularly enlarged and vaguely triangular (most visible in 
Figs. 49B
, 
54B
). Females are immediately identifiable by the opaque dark brown, apically pointed tibial spurs on the mid and hindlegs. Females may be otherwise determined by the following character combination: galea tessellate, dull; mandible with inferior tooth large, vaguely triangular, clearly angled off main blade (
Fig. 39B
); clypeal maculation an inverted-T, uncommonly interrupted above (
Fig. 39B
); supraclypeus strongly maculated, either trapezoidal or a widened pentagon; scutum shiny, with impunctate areas; and S5 with dark setae apically.

Male description.
Head: Facial maculations richly to pale yellow. Labral rim tridentate. Galea reaching rear of foretrochanter or nearly so in repose; medium to dark brown; usually strongly but sometimes moderately tessellate, with weak reflections. Mandible with inferior tooth large and triangular, clearly angled off main blade; maculated from base to near start of inferior tooth (
Fig. 49B
). Labral rim rounded; fully maculated. Clypeal maculation an inverted-T with slight depression to each side of medial upward-projecting line, reaching lateral sides, almost always reaching top medially (
Fig. 49B
); punctation only slightly sparser within maculation, near rim, than without. Paraocular area immaculate. Supraclypeal area strongly maculated; usually entirely filled. Scape maculated; fully along length and width below. Mesosoma: Scutum shiny; with distinct impunctate areas. Tegula transparent to slightly translucent, yellowish to light brown. Foreleg femur and tarsi elongate, basitarsus sinuate and spindly; basitarsus with unusual sculpted inner face and intricate setal tufts of white and black (
Figs. 49B
, 
54B
). Midleg more elongate: femur roughly equally so, basitarsus and especially other tarsi proportionally longer compared to foreleg (
Fig. 54B
). Hindleg only slightly elongate, mostly in tibia and basitarsus; femur, tibia, and basitarsus swollen, latter two seemingly forming clasping mechanism in conjunction (
Fig. 54B
); with unusually thick and long setae on inner faces. Basitibial plate absent; slight bump may be present anteriorly. Metasoma: T1 usually covered in appressed setae, sometimes with apical appressed setal band; T2–T4 with apical appressed setal bands, variable in thickness and often undulate; T5–T6 with or without apical appressed setal bands. Terga weakly to moderately tessellate between punctures, usually still with moderate reflections; sometimes still apparent through appressed setae. Tergal rims transparent, clear to slightly tan. Male T7 (
Fig. 59B
) without medial longitudinal carina; lateral projections only weakly recurved, blunt flanges; medial projections long and knife-like, the space between them usually filled by setae. Male S5 resembling 
Fig. 38D
, with dense and dark erect setal patches, but denser medially. Male S6 resembling 
Fig. 38B
, clearly medially emarginate with slight transparent integument near base, but with more transparent integument anteriorly and less setae covering rim. Male S7 (
Fig. 64B
) with setae restricted to sides around midpoint of length; widening from midpoint to tip, apical half widest near rounded lateral tips; apical half vaguely heart-shaped, rim rounded outward, with narrow medial emargination. Male S8 (
Fig. 69B
) lateral projections absent; medial projection narrowing to tip, where rounded at narrow medial point. Male genital capsule (
Fig. 74B
) with outer corners, where gonocoxite tips curve inward, nearly absent small bump, best seen in profile; from corner to apex, in profile, gonocoxite with low bump somewhat hidden to interior; tip, in profile, rounded and weakly curved ventrally; gonostylus tip position significantly exceeding that of gonocoxite, measured from above along primary axis of latter. Pubescence: See 
Fig. 54B
. Appears light to medium gray or overall, scutum sometimes tan. Setae white to off-white, though sometimes tan dorsally, except as follows: vertex and scutum only very rarely with any dark intermixing; legs highly variable, but tibia nearly always white; leg inner faces dark brown to black; tergal basal zones dark when present; T5–T6 with or without appressed setae; S5 thick patches always dark brownish.

